<div id="main_content">
	<h2>UCF Offering Free Workshops for Spanish Speakers With Children With Special Needs </h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Zenaida Gonzalez Kotala
		
		<span class="date">Feb. 27, 2007</span></p>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:tenfee05@hotmail.com">Mayra Ruiz Camacho</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-737-2586, ext. 50</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:zkotala@mail.ucf.edu">Zenaida Gonzalez Kotala</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-6120</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="index?page=article&amp;id=002400415bc28a54010f97070b370068ba"></a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>More than 20 parents and 19 children attended the first of four Spanish workshops at UCF for parents of children with special needs. </p><p>The three-hour sessions offer important information and insight into the Individual Education Plan, the most important document for special needs children in public schools. IEPs outline childrens diagnoses, what services they will get and goals for them to attain. They provide a road map for navigating through school. </p><p>I'm so excited, said Mayra Ruiz-Camacho, a doctoral student in the College of Education, who organized sessions. They are possible thanks to a research grant from the Toni Jennings Exceptional Education Institute at UCF. </p><p>She said more than 40 people registered and another 20 are on a waiting list. The sessions, which are in Spanish, continue each Saturday from 9:30 a.m. to 12:30 p.m. through March 31 at UCF. Free childcare is offered during each session. </p><p>What Ive discovered is that a lot of parents dont know about IEPs, Ruiz-Camacho said. They dont know they have a right to be a partner in creating it and can ask for changes. </p><p>Ruiz-Camacho said the workshops will help parents help their children get the best education possible. </p><p>The workshops also will yield valuable information for Ruiz-Camachos doctoral study. She is looking at what draws Hispanic parents to school meetings. </p><p>A lot of school districts offer these meetings, but get very poor attendance among Hispanics, she said. So they think its because they dont care or they dont want to be involved. But thats not likely the case. Perhaps they want the workshops in Spanish, or perhaps day care or cost is the issue. </p><p>At the end of the sessions, participants will be asked to fill out surveys, which will help Ruiz-Camacho determine what were the most important factors that attracted them. Then shell pass that information along with her study to school districts. </p><p>The only requirements for attending are that participants be 18 years old or older, that Spanish be their primary language and that they have a direct connection with a student who receives special education services in Orange, Osceola or Seminole counties. </p><p>Speakers will include a behavioral analyst and early intervention expert. Ruiz-Camacho is also inviting any professional who speaks Spanish and works in the area of special education to attend. </p><p>I want parents to see that there are people like them who work in the system and that can help them, Ruiz-Camacho said. I want them to attend and say, Hey, theres someone in my community who can help me. </p><p>Ruiz-Camacho said that as word spreads about the workshops, agencies are contacting her to provide material or speakers. On March 3 a representative from the Department of Education in Tallahassee are scheduled to present in Spanish during the session. </p>
		
	
	<p id="back"><a href="index?page=news">&lt; Back to the Newsroom</a></p>

